# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: iced-rust
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Elm was initially designed by Evan Czaplicki as his thesis in 2012.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] The first release of Elm came with many examples and an online editor that made it easy to try out in a web browser.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Czaplicki joined Prezi in 2013 to work on Elm, and in 2016 moved to NoRedInk as an Open Source Engineer, also starting the Elm Software Foundation.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] The initial implementation of the Elm compiler targets HyperText Markup Language (HTML), Cascading Style Sheets (CSS), and JavaScript.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] The set of core tools has continued to expand, now including a read–eval–print loop (REPL), package manager, time-travelling debugger, and installers for macOS and Windows.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Elm also has an ecosystem of community created libraries, and Ellie, an advanced online editor that allows saved work and including community libraries.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Elm has a small set of language constructs, including traditional if-expressions, let-expressions for storing local values, and case-expressions for pattern matching.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] As a functional language, it supports anonymous functions, functions as arguments, and functions can return functions, the latter often by partial application of curried functions.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Its semantics include immutable values, stateless functions, and static typing with type inference.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Elm programs render HTML through a virtual DOM, and may interoperate with other code by using "JavaScript as a service".
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] All values in Elm are immutable, meaning that a value cannot be modified after it is created.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Elm uses persistent data structures to implement its arrays, sets, and dictionaries in the standard library.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Type annotations are optional (due to type inference) but strongly encouraged.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Annotations exist on the line above the definition (unlike C-family languages where types and names are interspersed).
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Elm uses a single colon to mean "has type".
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Types include primitives like integers and strings, and basic data structures such as lists, tuples, and records.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Functions have types written with arrows, for example `round : Float -> Int`.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Custom types allow the programmer to create custom types to represent data in a way that matches the problem domain.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Types can refer to other types, for example a `List Int`.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Types are always capitalized; lowercase names are type variables.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] For example, a `List a` is a list of values of unknown type.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] It is the type of the empty list and of the argument to `List.length`, which is agnostic to the list's elements.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] There are a few special types that programmers create to interact with the Elm runtime.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] For example, `Html Msg` represents a (virtual) DOM tree whose event handlers all produce messages of type `Msg`.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Rather than allow any value to be implicitly nullable (such as JavaScript's `undefined` or a null pointer), Elm's standard library defines a `Maybe a` type.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Code that produces or handles an optional value does so explicitly using this type, and all other code is guaranteed a value of the claimed type is actually present.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Elm does not provide a mechanism to include custom types into these type classes or create new type classes (see Limits).
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Elm has a module system that allows users to break their code into smaller parts called modules.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Modules can hide implementation details such as helper functions, and group related code together.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Modules serve as a namespace for imported code, such as `Bitwise.and`.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Third party libraries (or packages) consist of one or more modules, and are available from the Elm Public Library.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] All libraries are versioned according to semver, which is enforced by the compiler and other tools.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] That is, removing a function or changing its type can only be done in a major release.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Elm uses an abstraction called ports to communicate with JavaScript.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] It allows values to flow in and out of Elm programs, making it possible to communicate between Elm and JavaScript.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Elm has a library called elm/html that a programmer can use to write HTML and CSS within Elm.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] It uses a virtual DOM approach to make updates efficient.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Elm does not officially support server-side development.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Czaplicki does consider it a primary goal, but public progress on this front has been slow.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Nevertheless, there are several independent projects which attempt to explore Elm on the backend.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] The primary full-stack Elm platform is Lamdera, an open-core "unfork" of Elm.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Czaplicki has also teased Elm Studio, a potential alternative to Lamdera, but it is not yet available to the public.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Czaplicki's demos seemingly use a future version of Elm that supports type-safe Postgres table generation.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] There is also speculation that that future versions of Elm would compile to C and use Emscripten to generate WASM, but this is unconfirmed by Czaplicki.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] For full-stack frameworks, as opposed to BaaS products, elm-pages is likely the most popular fully open-source option.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] It does not extend the Elm language (although it does use open-source components of the aforementioned Lamdera compiler), but rather runs the compiled JavaScript on Node.js.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] It also supports scripting using the `BackendTask` API.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] There is also Pine, an Elm to .NET compiler, which allows safe interop with C#, F#, and other CLR languages.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] There were also attempts in Elm versions prior to 0.19.0 to use the BEAM (Erlang virtual machine) to run Elm, but they are currently non-functional due to the removal of native code in 0.19.0 and changes to the package manager.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] One of the projects executed Elm directly on the environment, while another one compiled it to Elixir.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] The Elm Architecture is a software design pattern and as a TLA called TEA pattern for building interactive web applications.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Elm applications are naturally constructed in that way, but other projects may find the concept useful.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Those are the core of the Elm Architecture.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] For example, imagine an application that displays a number and a button that increments the number when pressed.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] In this case, all we need to store is one number, so our model can be as simple as `type alias Model = Int`.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] The `view` function would be defined with the `Html` library and display the number and button.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] For the number to be updated, we need to be able to send a message to the `update` function, which is done through a custom type such as `type Msg = Increase`.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] The `Increase` value is attached to the button defined in the `view` function such that when the button is clicked by a user, `Increase` is passed on to the `update` function, which can update the model by increasing the number.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] In the Elm Architecture, sending messages to `update` is the only way to change the state.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] In more sophisticated applications, messages may come from various sources: user interaction, initialization of the model, internal calls from `update`, subscriptions to external events (window resize, system clock, JavaScript interop...) and URL changes and requests.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] Elm does not support higher-kinded polymorphism, which related languages Haskell, Scala and PureScript offer, nor does Elm support the creation of type classes.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] This means that, for example, Elm does not have a generic `map` function which works across multiple data structures such as `List` and `Set`.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] In Elm, such functions are typically invoked qualified by their module name, for example calling `List.map` and `Set.map`.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] In Haskell or PureScript, there would be only one function `map`.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] This is a known feature request that is on Czaplicki's rough roadmap since at least 2015.
[src:iced-rust/elm-programming-language] On the other hand, implementations of TEA pattern in advanced languages like Scala does not suffer from such limitations and can benefit from Scala's type classes, type-level and kind-level programming constructs.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Traditionally used for desktop graphical user interfaces (GUIs), this pattern became popular for designing web applications.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Popular programming languages have MVC frameworks that facilitate the implementation of the pattern.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] One of the seminal insights in the early development of graphical user interfaces, MVC became one of the first approaches to describe and implement software constructs in terms of their responsibilities.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Trygve Reenskaug created MVC while working on Smalltalk-79 as a visiting scientist at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC) in the late 1970s.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] He wanted a pattern that could be used to structure any program where users interact with a large, convoluted data set.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] His design initially had four parts: Model, view, thing, and editor.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] After discussing it with the other Smalltalk developers, he and the rest of the group settled on model, view, and controller instead.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] In their final design, a model represents some part of the program purely and intuitively.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] A view is a visual representation of a model, retrieving data from the model to display to the user and passing requests back and forth between the user and the model.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] A controller is an organizational part of the user interface that lays out and coordinates multiple Views on the screen, and which receives user input and sends the appropriate messages to its underlying Views.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] This design also includes an Editor as a specialized kind of controller used to modify a particular view, and which is created through that view.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 supports a version of MVC that evolved from this one.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] It provides abstract `view` and `controller` classes as well as various concrete subclasses of each that represent different generic widgets.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] In this scheme, a `View` represents some way of displaying information to the user, and a `controller` represents some way for the user to interact with a `view`.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] A `view` is also coupled to a model object, but the structure of that object is left up to the application programmer.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] The Smalltalk-80 environment also includes an "MVC Inspector", a development tool for viewing the structure of a given model, view, and controller side-by-side.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] In 1988, an article in *The Journal of Object Technology* (JOT) by two ex-PARC employees presented MVC as a general "programming paradigm and methodology" for Smalltalk-80 developers.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] However, their scheme differed from both Reenskaug et al.'s and that presented by the Smalltalk-80 reference books.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] They defined a view as covering any graphical concern, with a controller being a more abstract, generally invisible object that receives user input and interacts with one or many views and only one model.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] The MVC pattern subsequently evolved, giving rise to variants such as hierarchical model–view–controller (HMVC), model–view–adapter (MVA), model–view–presenter (MVP), model–view–viewmodel (MVVM), and others that adapted MVC to different contexts.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] The use of the MVC pattern in web applications grew after the introduction of NeXT's WebObjects in 1996, which was originally written in Objective-C (that borrowed heavily from Smalltalk) and helped enforce MVC principles.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Later, the MVC pattern became popular with Java developers when WebObjects was ported to Java.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Later frameworks for Java, such as Spring (released in October 2002), continued the strong bond between Java and MVC.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] This is close to the approach taken by the Ruby on Rails web application framework (August 2004), which has the client send requests to the server via an in-browser view, these requests are handled by a controller on the server, and the controller communicates with the appropriate model objects.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] The Django framework (July 2005, for Python) put forward a similar "model-template-view" (MTV) take on the pattern, in which a view retrieves data from models and passes it to templates for display.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Both Rails and Django debuted with a strong emphasis on rapid deployment, which increased MVC's popularity outside the traditional enterprise environment in which it has long been popular.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] It is the application's dynamic data structure, independent of the user interface.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] It directly manages the data, logic and rules of the application.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, the design of a model type is left entirely to the programmer.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, Rails, and Django, a model type typically represents a table in the application's database.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] The model is essential for keeping the data organized and consistent.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] It ensures that the application's data behaves according to the defined rules and logic.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Any representation of information such as a chart, diagram or table.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Multiple views of the same information are possible, such as a bar chart for management and a tabular view for accountants.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, a view is just a visual representation of a model, and does not handle user input.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, a view represents a complete user interface element such as a menu or button, and does receive input from the user.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] In both Smalltalk-80 and WebObjects, however, views are meant to be general-purpose and composable.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, the role of the view is played by HTML templates, so in their scheme a view specifies an in-browser user interface rather than representing a user interface widget directly.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] (Django opts to call this kind of object a "template" in light of this.) This approach puts relatively less emphasis on small, composable views; a typical Rails view has a one-to-one relationship with a controller action.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 views communicate with both a model and a controller, whereas with WebObjects, a view talks only to a controller, which then talks to a model.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, a view/template is used by a controller/view when preparing a response to the client.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Accepts input and converts it to commands for the model or view.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] A Smalltalk-80 controller handles user input events, such as button presses or mouse movement.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] At any given time, each controller has one associated view and model, although one model object may hear from many different controllers.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Only one controller, the "active" controller, receives user input at any given time; a global window manager object is responsible for setting the current active controller.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] If user input prompts a change in a model, the controller will signal the model to change, but the model is then responsible for telling its views to update.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] In WebObjects, the views handle user input, and the controller mediates between the views and the models.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] There may be only one controller per application, or one controller per window.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Much of the application-specific logic is found in the controller.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] In Rails, requests arriving at the on-server application from the client are sent to a "router", which maps the request to a specific method of a specific controller.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Within that method, the controller interacts with the request data and any relevant model objects and prepares a response using a view.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Conventionally, each view has an associated controller; for example, if the application had a `client` view, it would typically have an associated `Clients` controller as well.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] However, developers are free to make other kinds of controllers if they wish.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Django calls the object playing this role a "view" instead of a controller.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] A Django view is a function that receives a web request and returns a web response.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] It may use templates to create the response.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] As with other software patterns, MVC expresses the "core of the solution" to a problem while allowing it to be adapted for each system.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Particular MVC designs can vary significantly from the traditional description here.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] As Alan Kay wrote in 2003, the original motivation behind the MVC was to allow creation of a graphical interface for any object.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] That was outlined in detail in Richard Pawson's book *Naked Objects*.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Although originally developed for desktop computing, MVC has been widely adopted as a design for World Wide Web applications in major programming languages.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Several web frameworks have been created that enforce the pattern.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] These software frameworks vary in their interpretations, mainly in the way that the MVC responsibilities are divided between the client and server.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Early MVC frameworks took a thin client approach that placed almost the entire model, view and controller logic on the server.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] In this approach, the client sends hyperlink requests or form submissions to the controller and then receives a complete and updated web page (or other document) from the view; the model exists entirely on the server.
[src:iced-rust/model-view-controller] Later frameworks have allowed the MVC components to execute partly on the client, using Ajax to synchronize data.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] In computing, **reactive programming** is a declarative programming paradigm concerned with data streams and the propagation of change.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] With this paradigm, it is possible to express static (e.g., arrays) or dynamic (e.g., event emitters) data streams with ease, and also communicate that an inferred dependency within the associated execution model exists, which facilitates the automatic propagation of the changed data flow.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] For example, in *imperative* programming, `a := b + c` would mean that `a` is being assigned the result of `b + c` at the time the expression is evaluated, and later, the values of `b` and `c` can be changed with no effect on the value of `a`.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] In contrast, in *reactive* programming, the value of `a` is automatically updated whenever the values of `b` or `c` change, without the program having to explicitly re-state the statement `a := b + c` to re-assign the value of `a`.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Another example is a hardware description language such as Verilog, where reactive programming enables changes to be modeled as they propagate through circuits.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has been proposed as a way to simplify creating interactive user interfaces and near-real-time computing animation.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] For example, in a model–view–controller (MVC) architecture, reactive programming can facilitate changes in an underlying *model* being reflected automatically in an associated *view*.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Several popular approaches are employed in creating reactive programming languages.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] One approach is the specification of *dedicated* languages that are specific to various *domain constraints*.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Such constraints usually are characterized by real-time, embedded computing or hardware description.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Another approach involves the specification of *general-purpose* languages that include support for reactivity.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Other approaches are articulated in the definition, and use of programming *libraries*, or *embedded domain-specific languages*, that enable reactivity alongside or atop a programming language.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Specification and use of these different approaches results in language *capability trade-offs*.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] In general, the more restricted a language is, the more its associated compilers and analysis programming tools are able to inform developers (e.g., in performing analysis for whether programs are able to execute in actual real-time).
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Functional trade-offs in specificity may result in deterioration of the general applicability of a language.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] A variety of models and semantics govern reactive programming.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Reactive programming language runtimes are represented by a graph that identifies the dependencies among the involved reactive values.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] In such a graph, *nodes* represent the act of computing, and *edges* model dependency relationships.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Such a runtime employs said graph, to help it keep track of the various computations, which must be executed anew, once an involved input changes value.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] At the implementation level, *event reaction* consists of the propagation across a graph's information, which characterizes the existence of change.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Consequently, computations that are affected by such change then become outdated and must be flagged for re-execution.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Such computations are then usually characterized by the transitive closure of the change (i.e., the full set of transitive dependencies a source affects) in its associated source.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] *Change propagation* may then lead to an update in the value of the graph's *sinks*.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Graph propagated information can consist of a node's complete state, i.e., the computation result of the involved node.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] In such cases, the node's previous output is then ignored.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Another method involves *delta propagation* i.e.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] In this case, information is proliferated along a graph's *edges,* which consist only of *delta*s describing how the previous node was changed.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] This approach is especially important when *nodes* hold large amounts of *state data*, which would otherwise be expensive to recompute from scratch.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Another common optimization is employment of *unary change accumulation* and *batch propagation*.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Such a solution can be faster because it reduces communication among involved nodes.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Optimization strategies can then be employed that reason about the nature of the changes contained within, and make alterations accordingly (e.g. two changes in the batch can cancel each other, and thus, simply be ignored).
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Yet another available approach, is described as *invalidity notification propagation*.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] This approach causes nodes with invalid input to pull updates, thus resulting in the update of their own outputs.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] A graph of dependencies is program-specific and generated by a programmer.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] When propagating changes, it is possible to pick propagation orders such that the value of an expression is not a natural consequence of the source program.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] We can illustrate this easily with an example.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Suppose `seconds` is a reactive value that changes every second to represent the current time (in seconds).
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Because `t` should always be greater than `seconds`, this expression should always evaluate to a true value.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Unfortunately, this can depend on the order of evaluation.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] When `seconds` changes, two expressions have to update: `seconds + 1` and the conditional.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] If the first evaluates before the second, then this invariant will hold.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] If, however, the conditional updates first, using the old value of `t` and the new value of `seconds`, then the expression will evaluate to a false value.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Some reactive languages are glitch-free and prove this property.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] This is usually achieved by topologically sorting expressions and updating values in topological order.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] This can, however, have performance implications, such as delaying the delivery of values (due to the order of propagation).
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Topological sorting of dependencies depends on the dependency graph being a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] In practice, a program may define a dependency graph that has cycles.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Usually, reactive programming languages expect such cycles to be "broken" by placing some element along a "back edge" to permit reactive updating to terminate.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Typically, languages provide an operator like `delay` that is used by the update mechanism for this purpose, since a `delay` implies that what follows must be evaluated in the "next time step" (allowing the current evaluation to terminate).
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Reactive languages typically assume that their expressions are purely functional.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] This allows an update mechanism to choose different orders in which to perform updates, and leave the specific order unspecified (thereby enabling optimizations).
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] When a reactive language is embedded in a programming language with state, however, it may be possible for programmers to perform mutable operations.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] How to make this interaction smooth remains an open problem.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] In some cases, it is possible to have principled partial solutions.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] In some reactive languages, the graph of dependencies is *static*, i.e., the graph is fixed throughout a program's execution.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] In other languages, the graph can be *dynamic*, i.e., it can change as the program executes.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Every second, the value of this expression changes to a different reactive expression, which `t + 1` then depends on.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Therefore, the graph of dependencies updates every second.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Permitting dynamic updating of dependencies provides significant expressive power (for instance, dynamic dependencies routinely occur in graphical user interface (GUI) programs).
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] However, the reactive update engine must decide whether to reconstruct expressions each time, or to keep an expression's node constructed but inactive; in the latter case, ensure that they do not participate in the computation when they are not supposed to be active.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Reactive programming languages can range from very explicit ones where data flows are set up by using arrows, to implicit where the data flows are derived from language constructs that look similar to those of imperative or functional programming.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] For example, in an implicitly lifted functional reactive programming (FRP), a function call might implicitly cause a node in a data flow graph to be constructed.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Reactive programming libraries for dynamic languages (such as the Lisp "Cells" and Python "Trellis" libraries) can construct a dependency graph from runtime analysis of the values read during a function's execution, allowing data flow specifications to be both implicit and dynamic.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Sometimes the term *reactive programming* refers to the architectural level of software engineering, where individual nodes in the data flow graph are ordinary programs that communicate with each other.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Reactive programming can be purely static where the data flows are set up statically, or be dynamic where the data flows can change during the execution of a program.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] The use of data switches in the data flow graph could to some extent make a static data flow graph appear as dynamic, and blur the distinction slightly.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] True dynamic reactive programming however could use imperative programming to reconstruct the data flow graph.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Reactive programming could be said to be of **higher order** if it supports the idea that data flows could be used to construct other data flows.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] That is, the resulting value out of a data flow is another data flow graph that is executed using the same evaluation model as the first.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Ideally all data changes are propagated instantly, but this cannot be assured in practice.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Instead, it might be necessary to give different parts of the data flow graph different evaluation priorities.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] This can be called **differentiated reactive programming**.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] For example, in a word processor, marking spelling errors need not be synchronized fully with adding or inserting characters.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Here, differentiated reactive programming can be used to give a spell checker lower priority, allowing it to be delayed while keeping other data flows more immediate.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] However, such differentiation introduces added design complexity.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] For example, deciding how to define the different data flow areas, and how to handle event passing between different data flow areas.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Evaluation of reactive programs is not necessarily based on how stack-based programming languages are evaluated.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Instead, when some data is changed, the change is propagated to all data that is derived partially or completely from the data that was changed.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] This change propagation could be achieved in a number of ways, where perhaps the most natural way is an invalidate/lazy-revalidate scheme.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] It could be problematic simply to naively propagate a change using a stack, because of potential exponential update complexity if the data structure has a certain shape.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] One such shape can be described as "repeated diamonds shape", and has the following structure: An→Bn→An+1, An→Cn→An+1, where n=1,2...
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] This problem could be overcome by propagating invalidation only when some data is not already invalidated, and later re-validate the data when needed using lazy evaluation.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] One inherent problem for reactive programming is that most computations that would be evaluated and forgotten in a normal programming language, needs to be represented in the memory as data-structures.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] This could potentially make reactive programming highly memory consuming.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] However, research on what is called *lowering* could potentially overcome this problem.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] On the other side, reactive programming is a form of what could be described as "explicit parallelism", and could therefore be beneficial for using the power of parallel hardware.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has principal similarities with the observer pattern commonly used in object-oriented programming.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] However, integrating the data flow concepts into the programming language would make it easier to express them and could therefore increase the granularity of the data flow graph.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] For example, the observer pattern commonly describes data flows between whole objects/classes, whereas object-oriented reactive programming could target the members of objects/classes.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] It is possible to fuse reactive programming with ordinary imperative programming.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] In such a paradigm, imperative programs operate upon reactive data structures.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Such a set-up is analogous to imperative constraint programming; however, while imperative constraint programming manages bidirectional data-flow constraints, imperative reactive programming manages one-way data-flow constraints.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] One reference implementation is the proposed Quantum runtime extension to JavaScript.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Object-oriented reactive programming (OORP) is a combination of object-oriented programming and reactive programming.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Perhaps the most natural way to make such a combination is this: instead of methods and fields, objects have *reactions* that automatically re-evaluate when the other reactions they depend on have been modified.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] If an OORP language maintains its imperative methods, it would also fall under the category of imperative reactive programming.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Functional reactive programming (FRP) is a programming paradigm for reactive programming on functional programming.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] The actor model (actors) is proposed to design reactive systems, often combined with functional reactive programming (FRP) and Reactive Streams to develop distributed reactive systems.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] A newer category of programming languages uses constraints (rules) as main programming concept.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] It consists of reactions to events, which keep all constraints satisfied.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] Not only does this facilitate event-based reactions, but it makes reactive programs instrumental to the correctness of software.
[src:iced-rust/reactive-programming] An example of a rule based reactive programming language is Ampersand, which is founded in relation algebra.
[src:iced-rust/retained-mode] Immediate mode is an alternative approach.
[src:iced-rust/retained-mode] Historically, retained mode has been the dominant style in GUI libraries; however, both can coexist in the same library and are not necessarily exclusionary in practice.
[src:iced-rust/retained-mode] In retained mode the client calls do not directly cause actual rendering, but instead update an abstract internal model (typically a list of objects) which is maintained within the library's data space.
[src:iced-rust/retained-mode] This allows the library to optimize when actual rendering takes place along with the processing of related objects.
[src:iced-rust/retained-mode] Example of coexistence with immediate mode in the same library is OpenGL.
[src:iced-rust/retained-mode] OpenGL has immediate mode functions that can use previously defined server side objects (textures, vertex buffers and index buffers, shaders, etc.) without resending unchanged data.
[src:iced-rust/retained-mode] Examples of retained mode rendering systems include Windows Presentation Foundation, SceneKit on macOS, and PHIGS.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:iced-rust/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] In JavaScript, WebGPU can be provided by a web browser or other JavaScript environment like Node.js and Deno.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] Rust and C++ can use their respective implementations of the WebGPU specification.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] Other languages like Python, Java, and Go can use WebGPU by extending the C language specification.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] Google Chrome and Microsoft Edge first released WebGPU support in April 2023.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] Safari debuted WebGPU support in June 2025 with Safari 26.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] Firefox first released WebGPU in July 2025 with Firefox 141.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] The W3C standard is a candidate recommendation.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] WebGPU enables 3D graphics within an HTML canvas.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] It also has robust support for general-purpose GPU computations.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] WebGPU uses its own shading language called WebGPU Shading Language (WGSL) that was designed to be trivially translatable to SPIR-V, until complaints caused redirection into a more traditional design, similar to other shading languages.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] Tint is a Google-made compiler for WGSL.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] Naga is a similar project developed for the needs of wgpu-rs.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] Both Google Chrome and Firefox support WebGPU and WGSL.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] Firefox and Deno use the Rust wgpu library.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] Safari follows upstream specifications of both WebGPU and WGSL.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] Chrome version 113 enabled initial WebGPU support on Windows devices with Direct3D 12, ChromeOS devices with Vulkan, and macOS with Metal.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] This support for Android was enabled in version 121.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] On June 8, 2016, Google showed "Explicit web graphics API" presentation to the WebGL working group (during the bi-annual face to face meeting).
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] The presentation explored the basic ideas and principles of building a new API to eventually replace WebGL, aka "WebGL Next".
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] On January 24, 2017, Khronos hosted an IP-free meeting dedicated to discussion of "WebGL Next" ideas, collided with WebGL working group meeting in Vancouver.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] Google team presented the NXT prototype implementing a new API that could run in Chromium with OpenGL, or standalone with OpenGL and Metal.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] NXT borrowed concepts from all of Vulkan, Direct3D 12, and Metal native APIs.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] Apple and Mozilla representatives also showed their prototypes built on Safari and Servo correspondingly, both of which closely replicated the Metal API.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] On February 7, 2017, Apple's WebKit team proposed the creation of the W3C community group to design the API.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] At the same time they announced a technical proof of concept and proposal under the name "WebGPU", based on concepts in Apple's Metal.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] The WebGPU name was later adopted by the community group as a working name for the future standard rather than just Apple's initial proposal.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] The initial proposal has been renamed to "WebMetal" to avoid further confusion.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] The W3C "GPU for the Web" Community Group was launched on February 16, 2017.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] At this time, all of Apple, Google, and Mozilla had experiments in the area, but only Apple's proposal was officially submitted to the "gpuweb-proposals" repository.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] Shortly after, on March 21, 2017, Mozilla submitted a proposal for WebGL Next within Khronos repository, based on the Vulkan design.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] On June 1, 2018, citing "resolution on most-high level issues" in the cross-browser standardization effort, Google's Chrome team announced intent to implement the future WebGPU standard.
[src:iced-rust/webgpu] On 13 February, 2020, Google unveiled Tint as an alternative to WHLSL textual language proposal to WebGPU API, and the language eventually became the standardized WebGPU Shading Language (WGSL), and Tint became the name of compiler within Dawn, the WebGPU implementation of Chromium.
